The Increase Contrast and Reduce Transparency accessibility features should improve accessibility. However, before this change enabling them caused the background of action sheets to become medium grey and the text to become a slightly lighter grey, which made the text hard to read. This prevents the problem by avoiding the use of a blur effect view when Reduce Transparency is enabled and using white text when Increase Contrast is enabled to prevent it from being darkened.

There're a few comments in the code where I think something better should be done, but I'm not sure of the best way.

1. Where the TableViewBackgroundColor is defined I've written:

```swift
// It'd be better to compute this colour by blending Ink90 with grey to emulate the layering
// done when reduce transparency is disabled
return UIColor(rgb: 0x454558)
```

2. Where the darkerSystemColorsStatusDidChangeNotification observer is defined I've written:

```swift
// Is there a better way to have the text redrawn to make sure contrast isn't affected?
self.tableView.reloadData()
```

3. Where PhotonActionSheet.tintColor is defined I've changed to a computed property that returns white when  the user has enabled Increase Contrast. This prevents the text colour from being darkened when the setting is enabled. There may be a way to simply prevent a label from being affected by Increase Contrast, but I'm not aware of it.

```swift
// Light grey is darkened, which reduces contrast on a dark background,
// so use white instead when the user has enabled the Increase Contrast
// accessibility setting
if UIAccessibility.isDarkerSystemColorsEnabled {
    return UIConstants.Photon.White100
} else {
    return UIConstants.Photon.Grey10
}
```

